<TEXT>
with british prime minister margaret 
thatcher pledging to defend her countrys sovereign interests a 
rocky road still lies ahead for the 12nation european economic 
community as it moves toward closer economic and monetary union 
but in the view of many participants at this weeks eec summit 
mrs thatcher went a long way to shedding her image as the reluctant 
european adopting a more conciliatory approach and making 
concessions that just days ago seemed unthinkable 
i give thanks for mrs thatcher prime minister felipe 
gonzalez of spain who holds the communitys rotating presidency 
said at the end of the twoday summit tuesday 
if you had asked me a week ago i would not have believed that 
this would have been possible 
after hours of hard bargaining marked by sharp exchanges between 
mrs thatcher and president francois mitterrand of france the most 
enthusiastic supporter of monetary union the community agreed to 
introduce on july 1 1990 the initial stage of a program for closer 
economic ties 
mrs thatcher succeeded in blocking an automatic transition that 
would lead to a central bank and a single currency for the community 
but she did not kill off the currency and bank proposals which 
the two other largest community members of the community france and 
west germany regard as a key part of the drive toward a single 
market all trade barriers within the eec are to be dismantled in 
december 1992 
under the agreement that all the leaders endorsed an 
intergovernmental conference can be called by a simple majority any 
time after july 1990 to vote on changes to the communitys founding 
charter 
such changes would be needed to set up the single central banking 
system and currency 
mitterrand who takes over the eec presidency next month says he 
plans to call the intergovernmental conference next year likely 
forcing the showdown on close monetary integration 
community officials say the issue by one means or another is in 
play 
the movement has been started and i am tempted to say it is 
irreversible said jacques delors the head of the communitys 
executive body and head of a panel that wrote the report calling for 
a single currency and central bank 
i understand that political striptease contains a number of 
steps that are not automatically linked to each other added 
delors predicting further concessions from mrs thatcher 
he could be wrong 
mrs thatcher insists a common currency and central bank would 
strip the british parliament of sacrosanct rights to formulate 
financial policy and has suggested that in the end many other 
leaders would be equally reluctant to surrender these powers 
it takes away the power of the nationstate and takes away 
power which is at the heart of parliamentary democracy power over 
the budget power over the economy she said in a british 
television interview at the end of the conference 
but officials noted throughout madrid that she adopted a softer 
stance and she repeatedly stressed that britain is committed to 
europe 
her tone was substantially changed and in the community the 
tone can be as important as the substance said one eec official 
requesting anonymity now we all seem to be talking about the same 
sort of europe and providing we agree were living in the same sort 
of europe we can find a way to advance 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
editors note maureen johnson is based in london and covers 
british politics for the associated press 
</TEXT>
