<TEXT>
a city councilman held on to his job 
tuesday despite efforts by a smokers rights group to snuff out his 
political career for sponsoring a tough antismoking ordinance 
unofficial results showed city councilor richard chapman winning 
all 22 consolidated precincts in his northeast albuquerque district 
city clerk eleanor sanchez said 3669 people voted against the 
recall while 1359 voted for it 
im ecstatic said chapman 41 in most senses the vote was 
much larger than me it was a vote for strong leadership in 
albuquerque it was a vote for health promotion 
dorothy jameson a packaday smoker who is a member of smokers 
rights of new mexico said she was disappointed but said her group 
will continue to fight the ordinance chapman sponsored which banned 
most indoor smoking in public places as of april 19 it carries a 
100 fine for violators 
angered by the ordinance smokers rights got enough petition 
signatures within chapmans district to force the recall election 
chapman a nonsmoker said the recall election had given him a 
chance to begin his reelection campaign a little early 
recognition was very high said chapman who will be up for 
reelection in october 1991 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
smokers rights contended the council violated the civil rights of 
thousands of smokers by prohibiting smoking in such areas as art 
galleries shopping malls libraries theaters taxis buses and 
public work places 
chapman said he sponsored the bill because polls showed most 
people in albuquerque favored smoking restrictions 
chapman who campaigned doortodoor against the recall often 
in temperatures near 100 degrees said he was surprised by the 
amount of publicity the recall generated 
i didnt have to introduce myself very much he said 
</TEXT>
