frank h wardlaw who established scholarly 
publishing houses at the university of texas texas aampm university 
and the university of south carolina died monday at age 75 
wardlaw served at texas aampm from 1974 to 1978 during a 33year 
publishing career he oversaw printing of more than 700 books a 
longtime resident of fripp island sc wardlaw set all three 
university presses on the road to excellence after careers in 
journalism and teaching 
he was named in 1978 as a fellow of the texas institute of 
letters he was one of only eight people in the organizations 
history given such a distinction 
wardlaw also served as founding director of the university of 
texas press for 24 years before coming to texas aampm in 1974 he 
established the university of south carolina press in 1945 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
dorothy stimson bullitt a major figure in pacific 
northwest broadcasting and founder of the king broadcasting co 
died tuesday she was 97 
mrs bullitt heiress to a realestate fortune was a leading 
figure in the citys business and cultural life for more than 50 
years in 1947 she founded king broadcasting purchased a local am 
and fm radio station kevr and changed the call letters to king 
after king county 
mrs bullitt ran the outfit with fierce independence vowing 
never to sell air time to religious organizations that ban remains 
in place at king television which she purchased for 375000 from a 
merrill lynch employee who had built channel 5 himself and put it on 
the air on thanksgiving day 1948 
mrs bullitt retired as company president in 1962 but remained 
honorary chairman of the board she was replaced as president by her 
son stimson bullitt an attorney who was succeeded at the station 
by ancil payne in 1971 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
frank trapani a longtime jazz trumpeter with 
the dukes of dixieland died monday of a blood clot to the lungs he 
was 52 
trapani played with the orchestras of charlie barnett les elgard 
and billy may as well as with artists such as pearl bailey tony 
bennett lou rawls and quincy jones 
he was lead trumpeter with the dick stabile orchestra in new 
orleans for 12 years until 1974 when he joined the dukes of 
dixieland for the past 12 years he was the dukes front man the 
musician who introduced each number to the audience 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
sir alfred j ayer the british philosopher who 
helped popularize the notion that all philosophy can be reduced to 
linguistic analysis died tuesday after a lenghty respiratory 
illness at age 78 
ayers first book language truth and logic in 1936 was the 
first exposition of logical positivism in the english language 
the movement which ayer helped to develop in britain expounds 
the view that philosophical problems of the past can be reduced to 
linguistic analysis and that any idea that cannot in principle be 
verified by sensory observation is nonsensical 
ranging widely between the ideas of linguistic philosophers 
bertrand russell and ludwig wittgenstein it accepts that language 
must be strictly analyzed and redefined if there is any possibility 
of using it as an intelligible means of logical argument 
the philosophical school of linguistic analysts now dominates 
many british and american universities 
ayer also wrote the foundations of empirical knowledge in 
1940 and the problem of knowledge in 1956 as well as volumes of 
philosophical essays and histories of modern philosophy in which he 
extended the traditions of british empiricism 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
elizabeth henry 86 one of the founders of 
the meals on wheels program in this country died sunday of 
pneumonia 
in 1958 ms henry and two other members of the visiting nurses 
association started the program in rochester ny after they had 
witnessed its success in england 
their first delivery was 14 meals today meals on wheels is 
active in hundreds of us cities ensuring that those who cant 
provide for themselves have meals delivered five days a week 
ms henry a pastpresident of the national dietetic association 
retired from the visiting nurses association as a nutritionist in 
1968 
</TEXT>
