<TEXT>
energy secretary james d watkins is winning 
praise on capitol hill for opening the traditionally closed doors of 
federal nuclear weapons plants to independent safety checks by 
outside agencies 
watkins was touring an energy department waste dump in new mexico 
today and meeting with three governors to discuss a plan to give 
states a larger role in decisions about nuclear weapons production 
and waste management 
watkins on tuesday also renewed his attack on the departments 
past management of the weapons program 
the chickens have finally come home to roost watkins said 
after years of inattention to changing standards and demands 
regarding the environment safety and health 
managers failed to understand that weapons production goals can 
be met without sacrificing safety and protection of the environment 
he said 
watkins announced a series of steps he said will chart a new 
course for his department in ensuring that the 17 major weapons 
plants in 12 states comply with all state and federal environmental 
laws 
the weapons plants have been crippled in recent years by a series 
of mechanical failures safety lapses and delays in repair and 
construction plans the problems have left the united states for the 
first time without the ability to make tritium a radioactive gas 
needed to produce thermonuclear weapons 
watkins also announced he had abandoned hope of opening a nuclear 
waste dump in new mexico in september he said the waste isolation 
pilot plant near carlsbad required more review by experts outside 
the department he said he expected to open the plant next year but 
would not set a specific target date 
sen pete domenici rnm praised the decision 
we can only be encouraged by his intentions to make doe more 
credible in its operations especially by allowing outside entities 
more room to review doe operations he said 
watkins told a news conference at the energy department he is 
ordering talks with state governments on ways to let them 
independently check federal data on environmental issues and defense 
waste cleanup schedules for weapons plants within their borders 
the energy department worked out such a deal with colorado 
earlier this month after gov roy romer threatened to close the 
rocky flats weapons plant the fbi raided the plant on june 6 to 
search for evidence of illegal waste dumping 
watkins called the colorado accord a model for new doe 
cooperation with the states he was meeting today with romer new 
mexico gov garrey carruthers and gov cecil andrus of idaho 
continued operation of weapons plants in those three states are 
linked to the opening of the new mexico waste dump 
rep mike synar dokla who has urged watkins to postpone 
opening the waste dump because of doubts about its structural 
integrity said he was encouraged by watkins new emphasis on safety 
over weapons production 
admiral watkins statement is music to my ears synar 
said 
environmentalists were less enthusiastic 
we remain very skeptical of watkins because of his seeming 
unwillingness to have outside people involved in a meaningful way 
in decisions about the weapons plants said frances close hart who 
chairs the energy research foundation an environmental group based 
in columbia sc 
ms hart said watkins latest statements appear to indicate a 
change in approach but that it is too early to tell whether his 
plans will be put into action 
watkins said the department brought on much of the environmental 
and safety trouble itself by sticking to a tradition of secrecy and 
distrust of outside agencies 
the obstacles have been in our own house not with the 
states he said 
