<TEXT>
on the supreme courts decision on burning the flag 
 
june 22 
the lufkin texas daily news 
what could be as repugnant as burning an american flag 
a few things come close a cross burning in a front yard 
antisemitic statements scrawled across the side of a wall the 
humiliating harangue of an ethnic slur 
all of these things are allowed and protected as free speech 
under the constitution of the united states 
the fact is that liberty true liberty allows stupid and 
outrageous political beliefs it allows them even if no one else 
agrees it allows them even though they violate the bounds of human 
decency 
burning the flag is all of that and more it tramples on the 
sacrifices made by our fathers sons and brothers in protecting this 
nation it brands those who do it with a mark of ignorance none of 
us should ignore we may have to allow them to speak their piece 
but nothing commands us to listen 
but ironically the supreme court decision saying flagburning 
is legal takes something away from those who would do it let them 
take to the streets of moscow havana or beijing burn the flags of 
those nations and they will not find the same freedom of expression 
as painful as it is the supreme court decision shows again why 
america is different as long as that difference remains the flag 
stands for something that can never be burned 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
june 24 
kennebec journal augusta maine 
the outcry against the supreme court flagburning decision may be 
shortlived we are not dealing with an issue which involves enormous 
social and legal dilemmas such as abortion 
the concerns are symbolic going to the intent of how a flag is 
burned burning after all is the recommended method for disposal 
of worn flags so the physical act is irrelevant to the courts 
decision 
what is involved is what are we to do when an isolated protester 
burns the flag as an affront to the vast majority of americans who 
consider themselves patriotic and to the flag as a symbol of 
national unity and resolve 
do we punish the protester and possibly send him to jail or do 
we tolerate even an act we hate as a measure of our commitment to 
unfettered political speech 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
june 26 
the joplin mo globe 
the supreme court siphoned off much of the symbolism from the 
american flag to which symbolism is everything a majority of five 
justices reasoned if you can call it that that the first 
amendment protects protesters who burn the flag in political 
demonstrations in addition to sparking outrage from millions of 
americans the court invalidated flagdesecration laws in 48 states 
 
of course the flag the visible symbol embodying the nation is 
worthy of sensible care protected political speech is vital but not 
invulnerable to perceive obscene treatment of the flag as a command 
of the constitution is an obscenity in itself 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
june 24 
the news dispatch michigan city ind 
burning the flag may be a distasteful form of expression and 
it may be extremely wrongheaded but you cant protect the most 
reasoned and inspired free speech without at the same time 
protecting the speech of those who are wrong and perhaps even 
outrageous 
and burning or desecrating the flag does nothing to harm what the 
flag symbolizes there is delicious irony in the fact that a 
flagburner who thinks he is trashing the country and its system 
actually illustrates the remarkable amount of freedom we enjoy 
the flag bless it and what it stands for can take a little 
free speech and come back for more 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
june 23 
