forms of the drug said study coauthor joseph sambrook of the 
medical center on wednesday 
most heart attacks occur when a clot plugs an artery that feeds 
blood to part of the heart muscle tissue plasminogen activator 
called tpa can stop a heart attack by dissolving the clot 
but some patients who get tpa therapy develop another clot after 
the treatment stops putting them at risk for another heart attack 
if tpa can be made to remain active longer it may reduce the 
tendency toward forming clots after therapy stops said thomas j 
ryan chief of cardiology at boston university 
tpas effectiveness is limited not only by inactivation but also 
because the drug is removed from the bloodstream by the liver that 
is why animal studies are needed to assess persistence of altered 
versions said edgar haber president of the squibb institute for 
medical research in princeton nj 
some researchers have altered tpa to hamper removal by the liver 
and perhaps that approach can be combined with that of the new study 
to create a longerlasting drug haber said 
sambrook said a longerlasting tpa might make treatment cheaper 
because smaller doses could be used currently because a given dose 
works only briefly tpa must be given as a continuous infusion over 
a few hours he said 
the treatment costs about 2000 some 10 times that of using 
another clotbusting drug streptokinase which is administered as a 
single injection 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

