<TEXT>
the canadian museum of civilization opens thursday 
on the banks of the ottawa river giving canada an extravagant 
combination of hightech and culture aimed at luring more visitors 
to the national capital 
the government invested 214 million in the museum which forms 
an impressive triangle of national landmarks parliament hill is 
visible from the glassedin grand hall of the museum on the ontario 
side of the river is the national gallery of art 
the 24acre museum has two separate structures a glacier wing 
for exhibition space and a canadian shield wing for storage and 
administration 
architect douglas cardinal said one of his goals was to make the 
vividly curved building appear as if it were carved by the glaciers 
and all the forces of nature 
for years a debate has gone on in canada over what constitutes 
the countrys national identity and whether anything more complex 
than a royal canadian mounted police officer can legitimately be 
called a national symbol 
as such virtually every aspect of the museum can figure in the 
quest for a national identity 
the museum houses a major collection of pacific coast indian 
totem poles native art and artifacts and wiring for its hightech 
systems that could circle the globe 18 times 
museum director george macdonald likes to speak of the museum as 
being of the global village the term the late canadian media 
analyst marshall mcluhan used to describe the world as a single 
community formed as a result of mass media rapid travel and other 
developments 
the museums technological systems have been described as 
symbolic of the importance of communications in developing a vast 
but sparsely populated country of 26 million people 
the museum will be able to tie into communications systems 
elsewhere and use the technology for research and educational 
purposes as well as its own exhibitions 
there have been complaints the cost was excessive at a time of 
budgetary restraints and that the new museum is as much a theme park 
as a cultural center 
macdonald said the cost said to be more than triple the original 
budget actually was within 30 percent of the target 
perhaps most like a theme park is the history hall where 
visitors can pass through exhibits showing the settlement of canada 
from whaling in the 16th century to mining in the west 
costumed actors will roam through the sections with buildings 
and other props to dramatize past and present ways of life 
only 45 percent of the exhibitions planned for the more than 1 
million square feet of space were ready for opening day 
the rest will open gradually in the next few years 
