<TEXT>
the massachusetts state seal with its sword poised 
above the head of an indian and the latin motto by the sword we 
seek peace has endured for 209 years but some american indians 
say thats far too long 
on wednesday a group of wampanoag indians took the first step 
changing the emblem the legislatures state administration 
committee unanimously recommended a bill setting up a study 
commission on the seal 
the genocide of american indians has just begun to subside 
lately said john peters of mashpee known among his wampanoag 
friends as slow turtle weve had to get through a lot of turmoil 
just to be survivors this sword over the indians head encourages 
that kind of attitude toward us its all right to kill indians 
the seal dating back to 1780 and updated to its present form in 
1898 appears on state stationery legislation the state flag 
prominent public walls the cover of the state budget and the back 
of gov michael s dukakis official chair among other places 
in the center of the seal stands an indian clad in deerskin and 
holding a bow and arrow a right arm bearing an english broad sword 
is poised above the indian and the motto printed in latin on a 
ribbon around the shield translates by the sword we seek peace 
but peace only under liberty 
in completing a modernization of the seal in 1898 anthropologist 
charles willoughby used the skeleton of an indian unearthed in 
winthrop a town just northeast of boston for the scale of the 
body a living indian little shell of the ojibway tribe on lake 
superior agreed to model for the head the seal looked much the 
same prior to 1898 but different versions were in circulation and 
the state wanted a single authoritative seal 
a contemporary description of willoughbys efforts tells of red 
men and poor savages the author e h garrett writes 
during the progress of the work of preparing the seal many people 
objected that an indian did not and should not stand for the state 
of massachusetts 
state rep byron rushing said the yankee politicians who 
conferred over the seal that year cared little about the american 
indian 
there was a judgment made by a bunch of gentlemen one afternoon 
at the parker house hotel and im not sure what they were 
drinking said rushing a boston democrat who is a supporter of 
the study commission bill 
five members of the wampanoag tribe wearing street clothes and 
indian jewelry attended wednesdays legislative hearing and 
presented their case for a more sensitive view of the american 
indian 
if approved by the legislature the study commission would 
consist of two senate members three from the house three american 
indians and four other appointed or elected officials 
what we want to do here is not to make any radical changes but 
to clear up the errors rushing said 
one possible alternative proposed by the wampanoags looks like 
the current seal from a distance but depicts a pine tree instead of 
a sword over the indians head the indian is drawn to resemble 
indians who lived in massachusetts when english settlers first 
arrived 
and in the indians hand instead of a bow and arrow is a peace 
pipe 
