efforts by nuclear power supporters to simplify 
and shorten reactor licensing suffered a major setback wednesday in 
the house energy and commerce committee 
by a vote of 2220 the panel voted to omit from a nuclear 
regulatory commission budget bill a provision that would have 
allowed a utility to get both a construction permit and an operating 
license at the same time 
under current law the nuclear regulatory commission must hold 
hearings after construction is complete on whether to grant an 
operating license 
a major streamling of commission rules that took effect last 
month limits the issues that can be raised in hearings on an 
operating license but without legislation the commission may not do 
away with that step 
the industry believes the new commission rules will not amount to 
the simplification the commission expects and will not do enough to 
remove uncertainty 
the industry has complained for years that the twostage process 
takes too much time and causes too much financial risk since the 
second hearing opens the door to lastminute challenges that can 
kill plants that already are completed 
rep william dannemeyer rcalif earlier this month narrowly 
won an energy and commerce subcommittee vote to attach his onestage 
licensing amendment to the nrc spending bill for the 1990 fiscal 
year that starts oct 1 
the proposal was killed however in wednesdays vote by the full 
committee the panel was scheduled to continue debate on the 
spending bill thursday 
lando w zech the nrc chairman told a news conference wednesday 
at commission headquarters that he still believes the rule has set 
the stage for getting nuclear plants built in six years or less 
that is about half the time required currently 
zech who is retiring from the commission on friday cited the 
rule as one of the most important accomplishments of his three years 
as head of the agency he is completing five years on the 
commission following a 42year career in the navy 
he said he was confident that an 11year hiatus in new orders for 
nuclear plants would end and that public concerns about safety 
would be overcome 
nuclear power plants are safer today than they ever have 
been he said 
zech will be replaced as chairman by kenneth carr who has served 
on the commission since 1986 zech who turns 66 on thursday said 
