wednesday a limited ninemonth extension of the strategic petroleum 
reserve as the nations energy lifejacket in the event of another 
oil embargo 
the senate last week bowed to house demands for a limited 
extension temporarily giving up its plan to expand the reserves 
capacity from 750 million barrels of oil to 1 million barrels by 
early in the next century 
as approved by voice vote in both houses the legislation now 
authorizes the energy department to continue filling the reserve 
with 60000 to 78000 barrels of oil daily only through next march 
without the bills passage the presidents authority to draw 
upon the stockpile in order to counter a dramatic upsurge in oil 
prices from an embargo or other supply disruption would have expired 
june 30 
under current law bush can use the stockpile only in the event 
of a disruption in oil imports 
the senate would have expanded his authority to draw it down also 
if domestic supplies are interrupted such as when oil prices shot 
up dramatically after exxon valdez tanker spill off alaska this 
spring 
rep philip sharp dind chairman of the house energy and power 
subcommittee said that issue along with new proposals for financing 
the reserve such as leasing the oil from foreign suppliers rather 
than buying it will be studied during the next nine months 
the government has spent some 6 billion on building the reserve 
