<TEXT>
an agreement to abandon the beleaguered 
shoreham nuclear power plant cleared its final hurdle wednesday when 
long island lighting co shareholders overwhelmingly approved the 
deal 
we must now come together and end the controversy lilco 
chairman william catacosinos urged about 600 shareholders at the 
companys annual meeting its hurt all of us too much 
gov mario cuomo who helped negotiate the deal called the 
shareholders action historic and said their approval allows 
lilco to devote itself exclusively in the future to providing safe 
and reliable energy for long island at the lowest possible cost 
the shareholders also approved the terms of a settlement of a 
classaction racketeerinfluenced and corrupt organizations act suit 
filed against the utility it calls for lilco to refund 390 million 
to ratepayers as adjustments in monthly bills over a 10year period 
under the agreement lilco will resume payment of dividends to 
its shareholders which were suspended in 1984 when the uncertainty 
over shoreham brought lilco to the brink of bankruptcy preferred 
stockholders dividends will be retroactive to 1984 
shareholder approval of the deal to abandon shoreham was the 
final step before the settlement between lilco and the state to 
close the 55 billion shoreham plant could take effect 
lilco is now expected to seek permission from the federal nuclear 
regulatory commission to sell shoreham for 1 to the long island 
power authority a state agency lipa will then seek approval from 
the nrc to dismantle the plant 
lilco was not guaranteed any rate increases in exchange for 
agreeing to sell the plant cuomo predicted when the deal was 
announced that any hikes would be probably less than 45 percent a 
year lilco customers already pay among the highest electric rates 
in the nation 
state and local officials contend the area around the plant 
about 50 miles east of new york city on densely populated long 
island could not be safely evacuated in the event of an accident 
it would be the the first time a completed nuclear power plant 
will be closed without ever going on line 
a preliminary tally of about 85 percent of lilco shareholders 
indicated that shareholders voted approximately 82 million to 3 
million to accept the deal according to lilco spokesman james lois 
however the deal could lead to a new round of battles since 
federal department of energy officials have stated that they intend 
to block the sale and transfer of shoreham for dismantling they 
contend the reactor should be mothballed so that it could be 
activated if necessary to meet energy needs in the future 
it was the second time within a year that lilco shareholders 
voted approval to the statelilco settlement to abandon the shoreham 
facility 
the earlier deal stalled in december when the state legislature 
refused to consider a portion of the agreement that required its 
approval the portion gave authority to the state power authority to 
build power plants on long island in place of shoreham to meet peak 
electricity demands 
the legislators charged that the rates provided for in the 
agreement put a burden unfairly on lilco customers 
under the revised 1989 settlement reached in february 
legislative approval is not required 
in april the nrc granted a full operating license for shoreham 
after nearly a decadelong struggle to obtain the permit shoreham 
had only been licensed to operate at up to five percent of full 
power 
suffolk county filed suit against lilco in 1986 under the rico 
statute charging that lilco had lied to the state public service 
commission about costs and progress of shoreham in order to obtain 
electric rate increases 
a federal jury in brooklyn convicted lilco making the company 
liable for billions of dollars an attorney for the ratepayers 
settled the case for 390 million 
